1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is a Bill?

A Bill is a draft proposal of a law.
When passed by Parliament and approved by the President → it becomes an Act.

🔵 Types of Bills

There are 4 major types of Bills:

1️⃣ Ordinary Bill
2️⃣ Money Bill
3️⃣ Financial Bill
4️⃣ Constitutional Amendment Bill

🔹 1️⃣ Ordinary Bill
Can be introduced in either House
Needs approval of both Houses
President can:
Approve
Return
Withhold
🔴 2️⃣ Money Bill (Article 110)

Deals only with:

Taxation
Borrowing
Government expenditure

📌 Key Points:

Introduced only in Lok Sabha
Requires President’s recommendation
Rajya Sabha can only delay for 14 days
Speaker decides whether it is a Money Bill
🔵 3️⃣ Financial Bill
Related to financial matters but broader than Money Bill
Requires President’s recommendation
Must be passed by both Houses

📌 Types:

Financial Bill I
Financial Bill II
🔹 4️⃣ Constitutional Amendment Bill
Used to amend Constitution
Can be introduced in either House
Requires special majority

📌 No joint sitting allowed

🔹 Key Differences
Feature	Ordinary	Money	Financial	Amendment
House	Both	Lok Sabha only	Both	Both
RS Power	Equal	Limited	Equal	Equal
President	Can return	Cannot return	Can return	Must approve
🔹 Important Concepts
Joint Sitting → For Ordinary & Financial Bills
No Joint Sitting → Money & Constitutional Bills

